<article>
An <strong>enlargement</strong> about a centre of enlargement is a transformation that will produce 
a similar shape bigger than the original shape. In enlargement, the produced shape 
must be similar to the original with different size i.e. not <strong>congruent</strong> shapes. 
<strong>Congruent shapes</strong> have the same shape and the same size. There can also be a reduction 
which is the opposite of the enlargement. In <strong>reduction</strong>, the produced shape is similar, but 
smaller than the original shape.
<br>
<br>
<strong>Note:</strong> An enlargement requires a <strong>centre of enlargement</strong> and <strong>scale factor.</strong>
<br>
<br>
<strong>Example 1</strong>
<br>
<%= image_tag 'Enlargement-fig.png', alt:'enlargement image', class: 'carol' %>
<br>
<strong>Fig 1.0</strong>
<br>
The point O is the <strong>centre of enlargement.</strong>
<br>
∆A1B1C1 is the enlargement of ∆BCD. Therefore, symbol ∆ means triangle.
<br>
<br>
The shape before the enlargement is called <strong>object</strong> while the shape after enlargement is called <strong>image.</strong> In figure fig 1.0, the triangle in black is the object and the triangle in blue is the image.
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h2 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>The Properties of Enlargement</h2>
</div>
(i)	 All angles remain the same in the object and in the image.
<br>
(ii)	Each line in the object is parallel to the corresponding line in the image.
<br>
(iii)	The length of the sides is proportional to each other.
<br>
(iv)	Each side of the object is scaled by a scale factor e.g. if an enlargement has a scale factor of 3, it means each image side is 3 times the object side.
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Scale Factor</h3>
</div>
<strong>Scale factor</strong> is the ratio of the lengths of the corresponding sides in the image and its object. The scale factor has no unit.
<br>
<br>
<strong>In the figure 1.0 above;</strong>
<br>
<%= image_tag 'scale-factor.png', alt:'scale factor formula image', class: 'carol' %>
<br>
The scale factor may be <strong>positive, fractional or negative;</strong>
<br>
	(i) If a scale factor is <strong>positive</strong> e.g. 2, 3, 4 etc. It means the image is bigger than the object (original).
	<br>
  (ii) If the scale factor is <strong>fractional</strong> e.g. <sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub>, <sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>3</sub>, <sup>2</sup>&frasl;<sub>5</sub> etc. It means the image is smaller than the object (original), this is also known as <strong>reduction.</strong>
	<br>
  (iii) If the image is <strong>negative</strong> e.g. -2, -3, -1<sup>1</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub> etc. It means the image is on the other side of the centre of enlargement and turned upside down (<strong>inverted</strong>)
<br>
<%= image_tag 'Inversion-image.png', alt:'inverted image', class: 'carol' %>
<br>
<strong>Inverted Image</strong>
<br>
<br>
<strong>Example 2</strong>
<br>
Use these two similar triangles X and Y to find the sides’ <strong>m</strong> and <strong>n</strong>
<br>
<%= image_tag 'Triangle-enlarg.png', alt:'trianglular enlargement image', class: 'carol' %>
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
Calculate scale factor first;
<br>
Scale factor  = <sup>EF</sup>&frasl;<sub>BC</sub> = <sup>32</sup>&frasl;<sub>16</sub> = 2
<br>
Scale factor = <strong>2</strong>
<br>
<br>
To calculate <strong>m;</strong>
<br>
Scale factor = <sup>DF</sup>&frasl;<sub>AC</sub> ; DF = 24m, AC = m, scale factor = 2
<br>
2 = <sup>24</sup>&frasl;<sub>m</sub>  cross multiply;
<br>
2m = 24 divide both sides by 2;
<br>
<sup>2m</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub> = <sup>24</sup>&frasl;<sub>2</sub>
<br>
m = <strong>12m</strong>
<br>
<br>
To calculate <strong>n;</strong>
<br>
Scale factor = <sup>DE</sup>&frasl;<sub>AB</sub>; DE = n, AB = 20m, scale factor = 2
<br>
2 = <sup>n</sup>&frasl;<sub>20</sub>; cross multiply
<br>
n = 2 x 20
<br>
n = <strong>40m</strong>
<br>
<br>
<strong>Example 3</strong>
<br>
<%= image_tag 'triangle-enlargement2.png', alt:'right-angle enlargement image', class: 'carol' %>
<br>
